WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.100 --> 00:00:03.475
DAVE MARKS: Welcome again.

00:00:03.475 --> 00:00:04.350
My name's Dave Marks.

00:00:04.350 --> 00:00:08.850
And today we'll be hearing
from Kira Asatryan.

00:00:08.850 --> 00:00:11.160
Kira's a relationship
coach, author, blogger,

00:00:11.160 --> 00:00:12.190
and loneliness expert.

00:00:12.190 --> 00:00:14.900
She calls loneliness a problem
of epidemic proportions

00:00:14.900 --> 00:00:16.992
in our modern times and
writes about this topic

00:00:16.992 --> 00:00:18.450
for various online
blogs, including

00:00:18.450 --> 00:00:21.190
"Time," "Psychology
Today," "Psych Central,"

00:00:21.190 --> 00:00:21.949
and "Elite Daily."

00:00:21.949 --> 00:00:23.865
She's spent her career
researching, pondering,

00:00:23.865 --> 00:00:25.780
and reflecting upon
what specifically makes

00:00:25.780 --> 00:00:27.420
relationships good or bad.

00:00:27.420 --> 00:00:29.320
And now she's taken
all that knowledge

00:00:29.320 --> 00:00:31.970
and published her first book,
"Stop Being Lonely-- Three

00:00:31.970 --> 00:00:34.230
Simple Steps to Developing
Close Friendships and Deep

00:00:34.230 --> 00:00:35.189
Relationships."

00:00:35.189 --> 00:00:37.230
So we've been lucky to
get some subsidized copies

00:00:37.230 --> 00:00:38.400
through Google [INAUDIBLE].

00:00:38.400 --> 00:00:40.660
So please pick one up at the
back of the room before you

00:00:40.660 --> 00:00:42.520
go, and I'm sure she'd be
happy to sign them for you,

00:00:42.520 --> 00:00:44.895
if you can stick around for
a few minutes after the talk.

00:00:44.895 --> 00:00:47.560
And so with that, I'd like
to introduce to you Kira.

00:00:51.734 --> 00:00:53.650
KIRA ASATRYAN: Thank you
for coming, everyone.

00:00:53.650 --> 00:00:54.983
Hello, everyone on the internet.

00:00:57.601 --> 00:00:59.100
I don't have any
slides or anything.

00:00:59.100 --> 00:01:02.920
I just am going to talk a little
bit, because I want everybody

00:01:02.920 --> 00:01:05.470
who's listening to this to
kind of get the gist of what

00:01:05.470 --> 00:01:08.590
"Stop Being Lonely" is about
even if you don't end up

00:01:08.590 --> 00:01:10.260
reading it.

00:01:10.260 --> 00:01:12.110
So I figured I'd
start by just talking

00:01:12.110 --> 00:01:16.170
a little bit about how to
"Stop Being Lonely" came to be.

00:01:16.170 --> 00:01:18.040
When I started writing
it, my only goal

00:01:18.040 --> 00:01:19.770
was really to
write the book that

00:01:19.770 --> 00:01:24.760
would have helped me in my own
social life about 10 years ago.

00:01:24.760 --> 00:01:28.130
I'm 32 now, and my
loneliest period of my life

00:01:28.130 --> 00:01:32.510
was in college, which felt very
weird and unusual at the time.

00:01:32.510 --> 00:01:35.560
I found out now that it's
actually not that unusual.

00:01:35.560 --> 00:01:38.760
But at the time, I
really would have

00:01:38.760 --> 00:01:42.300
liked to have had a book
like "Stop Being Lonely."

00:01:42.300 --> 00:01:44.780
I have really dealt with
loneliness my whole life.

00:01:44.780 --> 00:01:49.350
I felt it for as long as
I can remember, really.

00:01:49.350 --> 00:01:50.810
And I would also
say that it's fair

00:01:50.810 --> 00:01:54.070
that I've dealt with my own
fair share of shyness and social

00:01:54.070 --> 00:01:59.802
anxiety, which, of course,
can co-occur with loneliness.

00:01:59.802 --> 00:02:01.260
But the issue for
me was not really

00:02:01.260 --> 00:02:03.340
that I was afraid to
interact with people,

00:02:03.340 --> 00:02:06.880
which is kind of the
hallmark of social anxiety.

00:02:06.880 --> 00:02:10.600
Most of the feedback that I
got from people was positive.

00:02:10.600 --> 00:02:13.960
Most people thought I was
generally nice and sweet.

00:02:13.960 --> 00:02:16.170
So I didn't really
avoid people because I

00:02:16.170 --> 00:02:18.500
feared their judgment.

00:02:18.500 --> 00:02:20.520
I avoided people
because I didn't really

00:02:20.520 --> 00:02:24.190
enjoy interacting with them
that much, at least not as much

00:02:24.190 --> 00:02:26.520
as everyone else seemed to.

00:02:26.520 --> 00:02:29.524
And this really
bothered me because I

00:02:29.524 --> 00:02:31.190
would tend to isolate
myself, and then I

00:02:31.190 --> 00:02:34.280
would become extremely
lonely when I was alone.

00:02:34.280 --> 00:02:37.600
And I thought, what
was wrong with me?

00:02:37.600 --> 00:02:39.320
Part of what compounded
my frustration

00:02:39.320 --> 00:02:40.861
with my own loneliness
was that there

00:02:40.861 --> 00:02:44.330
wasn't a terribly good
reason for me to be lonely.

00:02:44.330 --> 00:02:46.610
I have a really nice family.

00:02:46.610 --> 00:02:49.750
In high school, I had people
I could sit with at lunch.

00:02:49.750 --> 00:02:52.530
And as an adult, I had
boyfriends and acquaintances,

00:02:52.530 --> 00:02:57.159
and I just thought, shouldn't
these relationships be enough?

00:02:57.159 --> 00:02:58.700
But no matter how
many people I could

00:02:58.700 --> 00:03:02.000
put on my objective list
of people in my life,

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:05.040
the same thing always
really bothered me;

00:03:05.040 --> 00:03:06.670
I didn't know what
it was that made

00:03:06.670 --> 00:03:11.440
some relationships feel good
and others feel not so good.

00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:13.670
I didn't understand why
some of my interactions

00:03:13.670 --> 00:03:17.550
with some people were loneliness
remedies, while others felt

00:03:17.550 --> 00:03:20.660
like loneliness intensifiers.

00:03:20.660 --> 00:03:22.950
I really wanted to understand
the root cause of what

00:03:22.950 --> 00:03:24.610
made me feel close
to certain people

00:03:24.610 --> 00:03:27.270
and not close to other people.

00:03:27.270 --> 00:03:30.600
This was really the
central issue for me.

00:03:30.600 --> 00:03:34.140
Because not knowing what caused
that feeling of closeness,

00:03:34.140 --> 00:03:36.050
made every interaction
with every person

00:03:36.050 --> 00:03:40.630
feel risky, something
to be avoided.

00:03:40.630 --> 00:03:43.790
So in 2013, I left
my very techie job--

00:03:43.790 --> 00:03:46.880
I was a performance
marketer and I did growth

00:03:46.880 --> 00:03:49.740
at various Facebook
app companies.

00:03:49.740 --> 00:03:53.510
I ran Facebook
ads-- in an attempt

00:03:53.510 --> 00:03:56.010
to sort of answer some of
these questions for myself,

00:03:56.010 --> 00:04:00.290
and I became a relationship
coach and mediator.

00:04:00.290 --> 00:04:02.380
I spent the first
two years of those

00:04:02.380 --> 00:04:05.812
roughly three years that it's
been researching the science

00:04:05.812 --> 00:04:06.895
of intimate relationships.

00:04:09.980 --> 00:04:11.480
And I can summarize
what science has

00:04:11.480 --> 00:04:17.000
to say about relationships in
two words; they're complicated.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:20.190
And what I mean by
that is this; science

00:04:20.190 --> 00:04:22.720
has pinpointed tons and
tons and tons of things

00:04:22.720 --> 00:04:24.970
that you're supposed to do
to have a good relationship

00:04:24.970 --> 00:04:26.650
with someone.

00:04:26.650 --> 00:04:28.190
You're supposed to show empathy.

00:04:28.190 --> 00:04:29.730
You're supposed
to self-disclose,

00:04:29.730 --> 00:04:32.640
meaning talk about
yourself, but not too much.

00:04:32.640 --> 00:04:34.680
You're supposed to offer
practical assistance,

00:04:34.680 --> 00:04:36.190
but not right away.

00:04:36.190 --> 00:04:38.400
You're supposed to develop
interdependence, but not

00:04:38.400 --> 00:04:43.192
prematurely-- that's bad--
and so on and so forth.

00:04:43.192 --> 00:04:44.650
And while it all
kind of made sense

00:04:44.650 --> 00:04:47.430
to me, my next thought
was, can anybody really

00:04:47.430 --> 00:04:50.660
do all of this stuff?

00:04:50.660 --> 00:04:53.440
To me, this laundry list of
things you're supposed to have

00:04:53.440 --> 00:04:56.120
and things you're supposed to
do in relationships, things

00:04:56.120 --> 00:04:58.600
you're supposed to have,
like trust, communication,

00:04:58.600 --> 00:05:01.930
et cetera, et cetera, just
seemed really, really complex

00:05:01.930 --> 00:05:04.380
to put into practice.

00:05:04.380 --> 00:05:06.300
And in real life
interactions, especially

00:05:06.300 --> 00:05:09.150
if you have any amount
of social anxiety,

00:05:09.150 --> 00:05:11.444
it's extremely hard
to recall complexities

00:05:11.444 --> 00:05:13.110
around what you are
and are not supposed

00:05:13.110 --> 00:05:16.390
to do around other people,
or what you are and are not

00:05:16.390 --> 00:05:18.920
supposed to say to people.

00:05:18.920 --> 00:05:21.490
In fact, in my own experience,
convoluted do-this,

00:05:21.490 --> 00:05:26.190
don't-do-that advice make
social anxiety worse.

00:05:26.190 --> 00:05:30.280
So I asked myself, is there
any way to make this simple?

00:05:30.280 --> 00:05:32.940
Is there a way to streamline
what real research says

00:05:32.940 --> 00:05:35.130
about relationships
and sum it all up

00:05:35.130 --> 00:05:38.380
in some kind of practical way?

00:05:38.380 --> 00:05:40.940
I sat with this question
for a long time.

00:05:40.940 --> 00:05:43.050
And then the answer
just kind of came to me,

00:05:43.050 --> 00:05:45.460
as answers sometimes do.

00:05:45.460 --> 00:05:49.790
And the answer to me it was
this; knowing plus caring

00:05:49.790 --> 00:05:53.020
equals closeness.

00:05:53.020 --> 00:05:56.130
Closeness, which is the real
focus of "Stop Being Lonely,"

00:05:56.130 --> 00:05:58.590
is that thing that makes
some relationships feel

00:05:58.590 --> 00:06:01.305
good and others not feel good.

00:06:01.305 --> 00:06:03.180
It's the ingredient that
makes the difference

00:06:03.180 --> 00:06:05.471
between an interaction from
which you walk away feeling

00:06:05.471 --> 00:06:08.530
more lonely or less lonely.

00:06:08.530 --> 00:06:10.600
It is, really, for all
intents and purposes,

00:06:10.600 --> 00:06:12.820
the antidote to loneliness.

00:06:12.820 --> 00:06:15.100
And it's created through
just two things--

00:06:15.100 --> 00:06:18.420
knowing and carrying.

00:06:18.420 --> 00:06:20.760
All of those
scientifically proven bits

00:06:20.760 --> 00:06:23.910
of good relationship
stuff can pretty elegantly

00:06:23.910 --> 00:06:26.710
fit into these two categories.

00:06:26.710 --> 00:06:29.660
And what I like about
this formula, so to speak,

00:06:29.660 --> 00:06:32.080
is that it's very
easy to remember.

00:06:32.080 --> 00:06:34.110
All you really have to
do in a social situation

00:06:34.110 --> 00:06:35.660
is ask yourself,
should I be trying

00:06:35.660 --> 00:06:40.090
to know this person
or care about them?

00:06:40.090 --> 00:06:42.190
So before I dive into
what that really means

00:06:42.190 --> 00:06:43.790
and what it looks
like in real life,

00:06:43.790 --> 00:06:47.770
I want to circle back to
loneliness for a second,

00:06:47.770 --> 00:06:51.252
because loneliness these
days is really, really weird.

00:06:51.252 --> 00:06:53.210
In another time and place,
you would not really

00:06:53.210 --> 00:06:56.170
feel that lonely, unless
you did something wrong

00:06:56.170 --> 00:07:00.310
or for some reason were
shunned by your people.

00:07:00.310 --> 00:07:02.290
But today loneliness
is extremely

00:07:02.290 --> 00:07:06.137
frustrating and confusing
for many people.

00:07:06.137 --> 00:07:08.470
And the first thing that's
become abundantly clear to me

00:07:08.470 --> 00:07:11.800
through my work and
my own life experience

00:07:11.800 --> 00:07:13.650
is that modern day
loneliness is not

00:07:13.650 --> 00:07:17.980
caused by a lack of
people in one's life.

00:07:17.980 --> 00:07:20.300
Now, of course, literal
social isolation can cause,

00:07:20.300 --> 00:07:22.160
loneliness and social
isolation comes

00:07:22.160 --> 00:07:25.510
with its own list of issues.

00:07:25.510 --> 00:07:28.020
If you live out in a cabin
somewhere by yourself

00:07:28.020 --> 00:07:30.900
or you live in a very sparsely
populated town or something

00:07:30.900 --> 00:07:33.070
like that, loneliness
is going to be something

00:07:33.070 --> 00:07:35.960
that comes along with that.

00:07:35.960 --> 00:07:38.120
But there are a
plethora of studies

00:07:38.120 --> 00:07:40.710
that show that one person
can be physically alone,

00:07:40.710 --> 00:07:44.610
even for a pretty long
time, and feel totally fine.

00:07:44.610 --> 00:07:46.860
While another person can
have hundreds of friends

00:07:46.860 --> 00:07:50.230
and feel desperately lonely.

00:07:50.230 --> 00:07:54.730
So if loneliness and aloneness
are not the same thing, then

00:07:54.730 --> 00:07:57.320
what is loneliness?

00:07:57.320 --> 00:07:59.150
Well, first, it's a feeling.

00:07:59.150 --> 00:08:04.590
It's not an objective state
of being, like aloneness is.

00:08:04.590 --> 00:08:09.030
And it's actually a feeling
that's kind of hard to define.

00:08:09.030 --> 00:08:11.940
Science has a lot of different
definitions for what loneliness

00:08:11.940 --> 00:08:14.582
actually is, and when
it comes down to it,

00:08:14.582 --> 00:08:17.040
it's kind of just one of those
you-feel-it-when-you-feel-it

00:08:17.040 --> 00:08:19.720
feelings.

00:08:19.720 --> 00:08:23.520
So, for a moment, I want to
take myself back to high school.

00:08:23.520 --> 00:08:26.240
As I mentioned earlier, I had
people to sit with at lunch,

00:08:26.240 --> 00:08:28.690
and I was invited by fair
share of social activities

00:08:28.690 --> 00:08:29.897
in high school.

00:08:29.897 --> 00:08:31.480
And if somebody had
asked my teachers,

00:08:31.480 --> 00:08:33.530
does Kira have friends?

00:08:33.530 --> 00:08:36.580
They would have said,
yes, she has friends.

00:08:36.580 --> 00:08:38.909
But, one day, when I
was in the ninth grade,

00:08:38.909 --> 00:08:41.370
I had a freak
accident with a horse,

00:08:41.370 --> 00:08:46.130
and I broke my shoulder
and arm into 16 pieces,

00:08:46.130 --> 00:08:48.620
and I had to have a surgery
that's only ever performed

00:08:48.620 --> 00:08:51.450
on adult male rugby players.

00:08:51.450 --> 00:08:54.010
In fact, my surgeon had to
delay the surgery for a week

00:08:54.010 --> 00:08:55.652
so that he could go
learn how to do it.

00:08:58.220 --> 00:09:01.320
So it was kind of scary
stuff for a 13-year-old.

00:09:01.320 --> 00:09:04.110
And to my anguish, it seemed
to me that none of my friends

00:09:04.110 --> 00:09:06.820
really cared.

00:09:06.820 --> 00:09:10.320
Of course they noticed that
I was gone for a while.

00:09:10.320 --> 00:09:13.040
But once the story of what
had happened circulated,

00:09:13.040 --> 00:09:16.102
it seemed to me that their
curiosity was quenched.

00:09:16.102 --> 00:09:18.560
They figured they'd talk to me
about it when they got back,

00:09:18.560 --> 00:09:21.970
and they knew I
was basically OK.

00:09:21.970 --> 00:09:26.280
But the lack of seeming
concern broke my heart.

00:09:26.280 --> 00:09:28.710
It was then that I felt the
distinction between having

00:09:28.710 --> 00:09:32.990
friends and feeling close.

00:09:32.990 --> 00:09:35.820
And in our modern world, I
think that this distinction

00:09:35.820 --> 00:09:37.920
between literal
aloneness, or having

00:09:37.920 --> 00:09:41.540
no friends, and the subjective
feeling of loneliness

00:09:41.540 --> 00:09:44.110
is becoming ever more obvious.

00:09:44.110 --> 00:09:47.180
Everyone has Facebook friends.

00:09:47.180 --> 00:09:48.850
Everyone has a phone
full of contacts

00:09:48.850 --> 00:09:50.610
that they could
theoretically contact

00:09:50.610 --> 00:09:53.780
about anything at any time.

00:09:53.780 --> 00:09:56.000
But do we actually do this?

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:59.180
And does it really matter?

00:09:59.180 --> 00:10:01.090
Personal technology,
specifically

00:10:01.090 --> 00:10:03.690
the internet and mobile
phones, has made it

00:10:03.690 --> 00:10:07.670
so that we have people available
to us all the time, at least

00:10:07.670 --> 00:10:09.670
in theory.

00:10:09.670 --> 00:10:11.920
We never really need to
lose contact with someone.

00:10:11.920 --> 00:10:13.730
And if we do,
technology makes it

00:10:13.730 --> 00:10:16.830
so that we can meet someone new.

00:10:16.830 --> 00:10:19.010
In many ways, we have
less literal aloneness

00:10:19.010 --> 00:10:22.590
than any other
people have ever had.

00:10:22.590 --> 00:10:24.730
And yet, despite this
forever connectedness,

00:10:24.730 --> 00:10:26.930
levels of loneliness
are rising across

00:10:26.930 --> 00:10:29.720
the entire Western world.

00:10:29.720 --> 00:10:32.380
At any given moment,
one in five Americans,

00:10:32.380 --> 00:10:37.120
that's 60 million people,
is feeling lonely.

00:10:37.120 --> 00:10:42.630
And that's up at least 30%
since the '80s-- at least 30%.

00:10:42.630 --> 00:10:44.880
So what does that mean?

00:10:44.880 --> 00:10:47.190
I see these two
things taken together,

00:10:47.190 --> 00:10:50.790
that we have less aloneness,
yet more loneliness,

00:10:50.790 --> 00:10:53.460
to mean that it's not
experiencially enough to have

00:10:53.460 --> 00:10:55.575
people around you.

00:10:55.575 --> 00:10:57.340
And the goal should
not be to have

00:10:57.340 --> 00:11:01.800
more contacts in your phone or
more social media connections.

00:11:01.800 --> 00:11:04.410
The goal should be to replace
the negative experience

00:11:04.410 --> 00:11:06.910
of loneliness with the
very positive experience

00:11:06.910 --> 00:11:09.070
of closeness.

00:11:09.070 --> 00:11:11.910
Or to put it another way, it's
about quality, not quantity.

00:11:14.550 --> 00:11:17.690
How one perceives the quality
of one's relationships

00:11:17.690 --> 00:11:22.600
is vastly more important than
the number of relationships

00:11:22.600 --> 00:11:24.880
that one has.

00:11:24.880 --> 00:11:28.030
And to really feel the
difference between quality

00:11:28.030 --> 00:11:31.940
and quantity, I want to do
a tiny little visualization,

00:11:31.940 --> 00:11:34.089
because I'm a coach, and
we do stuff like this.

00:11:34.089 --> 00:11:35.422
So close your eyes for a second.

00:11:40.060 --> 00:11:42.328
Imagine that you're eating
a piece of stale bread.

00:11:46.519 --> 00:11:49.060
Now imagine that you're eating
the most delicious meal you've

00:11:49.060 --> 00:11:49.750
ever eaten.

00:11:53.086 --> 00:11:54.210
Do you feel the difference?

00:11:56.920 --> 00:11:59.360
OK, you can open your eyes.

00:11:59.360 --> 00:12:03.230
My point is that the difference
is not a functional difference.

00:12:03.230 --> 00:12:07.530
Both stale bread and a delicious
meal satisfy real hunger.

00:12:07.530 --> 00:12:08.992
The difference is qualitative.

00:12:08.992 --> 00:12:10.700
The differences in
the amount of pleasure

00:12:10.700 --> 00:12:13.700
you derive from the experience.

00:12:13.700 --> 00:12:15.130
In my opinion,
when we're lonely,

00:12:15.130 --> 00:12:17.280
we're not starving
for human interaction

00:12:17.280 --> 00:12:20.230
and just ready to take
anything we can get.

00:12:20.230 --> 00:12:24.470
We're hungry for a certain
pleasurable experience.

00:12:24.470 --> 00:12:28.740
We're hungry for a
little bit of closeness.

00:12:28.740 --> 00:12:30.690
So let's talk about
closeness and how

00:12:30.690 --> 00:12:33.262
to create it in your life.

00:12:33.262 --> 00:12:35.470
The word closeness has a
lot of different definitions

00:12:35.470 --> 00:12:37.130
in the social sciences.

00:12:37.130 --> 00:12:41.100
But, in my world, it has a
very specific definition.

00:12:41.100 --> 00:12:43.690
It means the experience
of having direct access

00:12:43.690 --> 00:12:48.270
to another person's inner
world, to her dreams, her fears,

00:12:48.270 --> 00:12:51.930
her habits, her
preferences, et cetera.

00:12:51.930 --> 00:12:54.870
Once you have direct access to
another person's inner world,

00:12:54.870 --> 00:12:58.000
you can sit next to her and
know what she's thinking.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:02.160
You can look into her eyes
and feel what she's feeling.

00:13:02.160 --> 00:13:04.400
And as I've said,
this is created

00:13:04.400 --> 00:13:07.240
through knowing and caring.

00:13:07.240 --> 00:13:09.610
Knowing, as I define
it, means being

00:13:09.610 --> 00:13:14.790
able to see someone's life
from their own perspective.

00:13:14.790 --> 00:13:17.060
And caring means expressing
interest and investment

00:13:17.060 --> 00:13:20.380
in that person's well-being.

00:13:20.380 --> 00:13:23.970
So let's talk a
little about knowing.

00:13:23.970 --> 00:13:25.500
Knowing, in the
sense that I use it,

00:13:25.500 --> 00:13:27.499
is actually pretty different
from how we usually

00:13:27.499 --> 00:13:29.480
know people.

00:13:29.480 --> 00:13:31.070
We tend to think we
know someone when

00:13:31.070 --> 00:13:33.750
we've interacted with
them a lot and developed

00:13:33.750 --> 00:13:36.550
a theory of how they are.

00:13:36.550 --> 00:13:39.390
My cousin Lisa is
a total pushover.

00:13:39.390 --> 00:13:42.400
My old boss had anger issues.

00:13:42.400 --> 00:13:46.730
My best friend is the most
dependable person in the world.

00:13:46.730 --> 00:13:48.630
While these things
may be true for me,

00:13:48.630 --> 00:13:50.840
as you can probably
see, they are

00:13:50.840 --> 00:13:54.660
evaluations that I have
made of this other person.

00:13:54.660 --> 00:13:57.670
They're my perceptions.

00:13:57.670 --> 00:14:00.940
Take the last example
of my best friend.

00:14:00.940 --> 00:14:04.200
I may experience her
as being dependable.

00:14:04.200 --> 00:14:06.450
But from her
perspective, she may

00:14:06.450 --> 00:14:09.270
experience her own
dependability as anxiety

00:14:09.270 --> 00:14:11.010
about not wanting
to let anybody down.

00:14:16.060 --> 00:14:17.435
Until I understand
her experience

00:14:17.435 --> 00:14:20.397
of her own dependability
from her perspective,

00:14:20.397 --> 00:14:21.980
I don't really know
her and a way that

00:14:21.980 --> 00:14:25.716
makes her feel close to me.

00:14:25.716 --> 00:14:27.590
In the same way, the
way that I define caring

00:14:27.590 --> 00:14:29.170
is kind of different
than how we usually

00:14:29.170 --> 00:14:30.211
try to care about people.

00:14:32.960 --> 00:14:36.470
In our culture, we
usually show caring

00:14:36.470 --> 00:14:40.410
by either worrying about someone
or trying to give them advice.

00:14:40.410 --> 00:14:43.320
And, unfortunately, neither
one of these mechanics

00:14:43.320 --> 00:14:47.020
work that well for
creating closeness.

00:14:47.020 --> 00:14:49.600
Giving advice, which is usually
really well-intentioned,

00:14:49.600 --> 00:14:52.320
doesn't work that well
because it actually places you

00:14:52.320 --> 00:14:55.490
in a superior position,
as the one who

00:14:55.490 --> 00:14:57.810
knows things or the
one who can fix things

00:14:57.810 --> 00:15:00.220
for the other person,
which actually kind

00:15:00.220 --> 00:15:03.410
of seeds resentment in them.

00:15:03.410 --> 00:15:05.310
Expressing concern
through worrying

00:15:05.310 --> 00:15:07.930
doesn't really work
that well either

00:15:07.930 --> 00:15:09.430
because it prompts
the other person

00:15:09.430 --> 00:15:12.280
to try to prove that
everything is OK with them

00:15:12.280 --> 00:15:15.930
to ease your discomfort.

00:15:15.930 --> 00:15:18.700
Instead, the kind of
caring that I talk about

00:15:18.700 --> 00:15:20.510
is just the act of
simply expressing

00:15:20.510 --> 00:15:25.660
interest and an investment in
the other person's well-being,

00:15:25.660 --> 00:15:29.460
and it opens the door
for emotional connection.

00:15:29.460 --> 00:15:32.120
It says to the other
person, I'm here.

00:15:32.120 --> 00:15:33.640
I'm listening to you.

00:15:33.640 --> 00:15:37.010
What would you like to say?

00:15:37.010 --> 00:15:40.280
Together, knowing
and caring work well

00:15:40.280 --> 00:15:44.810
because they are a
powerful combination.

00:15:44.810 --> 00:15:47.940
They communicate not
only do I really see you,

00:15:47.940 --> 00:15:50.070
I'm listening to you.

00:15:50.070 --> 00:15:52.900
Not only do I understand
you, I also value you.

00:15:55.430 --> 00:15:57.320
So have you ever had
that experience where

00:15:57.320 --> 00:15:59.020
you learn a new
word and then you

00:15:59.020 --> 00:16:01.607
start hearing it everywhere?

00:16:01.607 --> 00:16:03.690
That's kind of what happened
to me after I came up

00:16:03.690 --> 00:16:07.010
with this knowing plus caring
equals closeness thing.

00:16:07.010 --> 00:16:09.990
I started seeing it pop
up all over the place

00:16:09.990 --> 00:16:12.120
in the unconscious phrasing
of some of the most

00:16:12.120 --> 00:16:15.808
famous relationship experts.

00:16:15.808 --> 00:16:18.150
Is anybody here familiar with
the "Five Love Languages?"

00:16:18.150 --> 00:16:20.636
It's like the most famous
love book out there.

00:16:20.636 --> 00:16:25.640
In it, Gary Chapman says,
"with verbal encouragement,

00:16:25.640 --> 00:16:28.150
we are trying to
communicate 'I know.

00:16:28.150 --> 00:16:28.880
I care.

00:16:28.880 --> 00:16:33.020
How can I help?'"
Psychologist, researcher,

00:16:33.020 --> 00:16:34.540
and bestselling
author John Gottman,

00:16:34.540 --> 00:16:38.410
and he's also my personal crush,
ends in anecdote from his book

00:16:38.410 --> 00:16:40.582
"What Makes Love
Last" by saying,

00:16:40.582 --> 00:16:44.040
"a husband I once helped came
to accept that he could not

00:16:44.040 --> 00:16:47.710
control what his wife feels,
and that it's not his job to get

00:16:47.710 --> 00:16:51.900
her to cheer up, calm down,
or develop a sense of humor.

00:16:51.900 --> 00:16:56.680
All she needs is for him
to know her and care."

00:16:56.680 --> 00:16:58.520
The type of loneliness
that most of us

00:16:58.520 --> 00:17:00.960
are experiencing these
days is fundamentally

00:17:00.960 --> 00:17:03.320
an internal loneliness,
a loneliness

00:17:03.320 --> 00:17:05.740
of the heart and mind.

00:17:05.740 --> 00:17:08.240
Knowing someone well and
caring about them deeply

00:17:08.240 --> 00:17:11.650
creates a mental and emotional
closeness, or a closeness

00:17:11.650 --> 00:17:13.920
of the heart and mind.

00:17:13.920 --> 00:17:16.650
And by eliminating
this internal distance,

00:17:16.650 --> 00:17:20.329
closeness eliminates the sadness
that comes with it, also known

00:17:20.329 --> 00:17:22.640
as loneliness.

00:17:22.640 --> 00:17:24.619
In this way, closeness
acts as the opposite

00:17:24.619 --> 00:17:28.970
of loneliness and the
antidote to its effects.

00:17:28.970 --> 00:17:32.210
So to wrap things up, just one
more thing-- and this thing

00:17:32.210 --> 00:17:35.410
is important;
closeness is something

00:17:35.410 --> 00:17:37.070
that is within your
control to create

00:17:37.070 --> 00:17:40.270
with anyone who also wants it.

00:17:40.270 --> 00:17:44.330
So it really is something
that you can start having now.

00:17:44.330 --> 00:17:48.850
So what could you do to start
feeling less lonely right now?

00:17:48.850 --> 00:17:52.050
So I will save you any
icebreakers or friendship

00:17:52.050 --> 00:17:55.089
pick-up lines, which
sometimes people ask me for,

00:17:55.089 --> 00:17:56.630
and instead just
talk about something

00:17:56.630 --> 00:17:59.190
quickly from the book.

00:17:59.190 --> 00:18:02.200
It's an idea called "separate
the person from the problem."

00:18:02.200 --> 00:18:06.360
And I didn't come up with it;
it's from business negotiation.

00:18:06.360 --> 00:18:08.820
The premise of separate
the person from the problem

00:18:08.820 --> 00:18:10.950
is that to maintain
positive relationships

00:18:10.950 --> 00:18:15.210
during hard times, one must
think of people and problems

00:18:15.210 --> 00:18:18.127
as separate entities.

00:18:18.127 --> 00:18:19.710
In other words, it's
easier to come up

00:18:19.710 --> 00:18:24.400
with a resolution with someone
when you don't view them

00:18:24.400 --> 00:18:26.990
as the problem.

00:18:26.990 --> 00:18:28.490
Once you make this
distinction, you

00:18:28.490 --> 00:18:30.440
can treat the person
with love and respect

00:18:30.440 --> 00:18:34.070
and thoroughly
eliminate the problem.

00:18:34.070 --> 00:18:35.960
So one thing you
can do right now

00:18:35.960 --> 00:18:40.210
to start feeling less lonely
is to start separating yourself

00:18:40.210 --> 00:18:42.970
from the problem of loneliness.

00:18:42.970 --> 00:18:46.900
You are really not to blame
if you're feeling lonely.

00:18:46.900 --> 00:18:49.870
You are a precious
person who is deserving

00:18:49.870 --> 00:18:52.080
of love and closeness,
and loneliness

00:18:52.080 --> 00:18:56.902
is a problem outside of you that
can be thoroughly eliminated.

00:18:56.902 --> 00:18:57.818
And that's all I have.

