actually a good example.

00:27:07.260 --> 00:27:08.884
If you work at Google,
there's probably

00:27:08.884 --> 00:27:12.380
people around you who would
be interested in being

00:27:12.380 --> 00:27:13.050
closer to you.

00:27:17.002 --> 00:27:19.324
If you're very, very isolated,
that's more difficult.

00:27:19.324 --> 00:27:21.337
But I would say
anybody who approaches

00:27:21.337 --> 00:27:25.436
you to talk about
anything outside of work

00:27:25.436 --> 00:27:26.810
is probably
interested in getting

00:27:26.810 --> 00:27:28.200
to know you as a person.

00:27:31.880 --> 00:27:33.249
AUDIENCE: I have one, actually.

00:27:33.249 --> 00:27:35.040
I don't know if I can
articulate very well,

00:27:35.040 --> 00:27:37.912
so you'll have to bear with me.

00:27:37.912 --> 00:27:40.370
The gentleman who asked about
his daughter actually kind of

00:27:40.370 --> 00:27:42.720
gave me a vehicle to
ask this question.

00:27:42.720 --> 00:27:46.504
So you mentioned quality
over quantity, right?

00:27:46.504 --> 00:27:49.280
So let's extrapolate
that for a moment.

00:27:49.280 --> 00:27:51.750
So we have 1,000
Facebook friends.

00:27:51.750 --> 00:27:52.610
That's quantity.

00:27:52.610 --> 00:27:55.380
But if we can five or
10 friends with whom

00:27:55.380 --> 00:27:58.230
we have that intimacy,
that caring you describe,

00:27:58.230 --> 00:27:59.740
we're probably doing better.

00:27:59.740 --> 00:28:02.200
If we take that further
though, because I

00:28:02.200 --> 00:28:04.450
will attest to that
maybe on a Friday,

00:28:04.450 --> 00:28:06.730
going out with a
very good friend

00:28:06.730 --> 00:28:08.880
and having like a nice
conversation with them

00:28:08.880 --> 00:28:11.150
and feeling cared for,
but still [INAUDIBLE]

00:28:11.150 --> 00:28:14.900
go home and still a little empty
even after that interaction.

00:28:14.900 --> 00:28:19.459
If you can have even one friend
who really kind of gets you,

00:28:19.459 --> 00:28:20.500
that can be kind of cool.

00:28:20.500 --> 00:28:22.780
So where I'm going with
this is that friend

00:28:22.780 --> 00:28:24.820
might be you perhaps.

00:28:24.820 --> 00:28:30.230
And the reason is, you mentioned
the public persona, right?

00:28:30.230 --> 00:28:32.255
12- to 22-year-olds,
probably more so

00:28:32.255 --> 00:28:34.490
than any other
demographic, probably

00:28:34.490 --> 00:28:38.070
know themselves the least
and are figuring it out.

00:28:38.070 --> 00:28:41.180
So is some of it maybe
not on us, in a way,

00:28:41.180 --> 00:28:45.504
to really accept who we are, and
have intimacy with ourselves?

00:28:45.504 --> 00:28:48.170
KIRA ASATRYAN: Totally, that's a
really good question, because I

00:28:48.170 --> 00:28:50.756
actually, in the first
draft of this book,

00:28:50.756 --> 00:28:53.870
I didn't have
anything about that,

00:28:53.870 --> 00:28:55.812
about getting
closer to yourself.

00:28:55.812 --> 00:28:57.270
And my editor was
like, you're kind

00:28:57.270 --> 00:29:00.350
of expecting that people
have done a lot of self-work

00:29:00.350 --> 00:29:02.970
already, and she was right.

00:29:02.970 --> 00:29:05.240
I was kind of assuming that.

00:29:05.240 --> 00:29:06.790
So there is a
chapter in there now

00:29:06.790 --> 00:29:09.840
about having do knowing
and caring with yourself.

00:29:09.840 --> 00:29:12.410
Self-care is actually
a big thing right now.

00:29:12.410 --> 00:29:15.420
Like if you're in
the self-help world,

00:29:15.420 --> 00:29:18.060
self-care is like a very
trendy thing right now.

00:29:18.060 --> 00:29:19.050
But it's real.

00:29:19.050 --> 00:29:20.200
It works.

00:29:20.200 --> 00:29:22.057
Making time for
yourself and doing

00:29:22.057 --> 00:29:25.220
the things that
kind of replenish

00:29:25.220 --> 00:29:28.723
you are pretty important,
and getting to know yourself,

00:29:28.723 --> 00:29:32.327
of course-- you're own needs
and values and motivation.

00:29:32.327 --> 00:29:33.160
AUDIENCE: Very cool.

00:29:33.160 --> 00:29:34.201
Thank you for that, yeah.

00:29:37.612 --> 00:29:40.070
DAVE MARKS: I was going to say,
I identify as an introvert,

00:29:40.070 --> 00:29:40.570
right?

00:29:40.570 --> 00:29:44.110
And I very much so
like enjoy getting

00:29:44.110 --> 00:29:46.540
to know myself and like
thinking through my emotions

00:29:46.540 --> 00:29:47.320
and feelings.

00:29:47.320 --> 00:29:49.210
And sometimes it's
super energizing.

00:29:49.210 --> 00:29:50.960
But I notice that it
hits this point where

00:29:50.960 --> 00:29:53.211
it becomes pretty isolating.

00:29:53.211 --> 00:29:55.835
Do you have any vision on how we
can balance it better or flags

00:29:55.835 --> 00:29:59.060
we can look for in ourselves
to know when we are recharging

00:29:59.060 --> 00:30:01.546
versus going into a lonely hole?

00:30:01.546 --> 00:30:03.170
KIRA ASATRYAN: Yeah,
there is a version

00:30:03.170 --> 00:30:08.910
of isolating yourself or being
alone that's really positive.

00:30:08.910 --> 00:30:10.640
It's like solitude.

00:30:10.640 --> 00:30:12.360
And I'm totally
an introvert too.

00:30:12.360 --> 00:30:16.297
And I think that my
introvertedness seeps through

00:30:16.297 --> 00:30:16.880
into the book.

00:30:16.880 --> 00:30:19.080
It kind of has that
perspective that

00:30:19.080 --> 00:30:23.310
assumes that sometimes
people like to be alone.

00:30:23.310 --> 00:30:26.200
But, like I said, the
loneliness-versus-closeness

00:30:26.200 --> 00:30:28.370
thing is really,
really subjective.

00:30:28.370 --> 00:30:30.845
So if you kind of
are keeping tabs

00:30:30.845 --> 00:30:32.934
on how your aloneness
is making you feel,

00:30:32.934 --> 00:30:37.610
you can probably identify when
that switch starts to happen.

00:30:37.610 --> 00:30:42.945
The thing about loneliness
is that it's really bad

00:30:42.945 --> 00:30:45.410
when you feel like
you can't stop it,

00:30:45.410 --> 00:30:47.150
like when you feel
like, OK, I am

00:30:47.150 --> 00:30:51.284
aware that it's switched over
into this feeling bad thing.

00:30:51.284 --> 00:30:54.370
But I don't know what to do.

00:30:54.370 --> 00:30:57.055
So that was the issue that
I was trying to speak to.

00:30:57.055 --> 00:30:59.180
DAVE MARKS: So it's all
new tools to get out of it.

00:30:59.180 --> 00:31:00.902
Once you notice it,
you'll be all right.

00:31:00.902 --> 00:31:03.360
A lot of times people ask me
like, are you a people person?

00:31:03.360 --> 00:31:07.250
And my response is, I like
to be alone until I'm lonely.

00:31:07.250 --> 00:31:09.580
KIRA ASATRYAN: Right, exactly.

00:31:09.580 --> 00:31:11.300
DAVE MARKS: That's how its.

00:31:11.300 --> 00:31:13.130
AUDIENCE: So,
multi-part question,

00:31:13.130 --> 00:31:16.760
all related to my
12-year-old daughter.

00:31:16.760 --> 00:31:19.370
I could probably ask you
a lot more afterwards.

00:31:19.370 --> 00:31:24.230
But you mentioned that you felt
lonely when you were 13, right?

00:31:24.230 --> 00:31:28.420
Is there a section in your book
which talks a little bit more

00:31:28.420 --> 00:31:30.420
about your background
at 13 years old

00:31:30.420 --> 00:31:31.410
and your state of mind?

00:31:31.410 --> 00:31:32.690
And so that's one part.

00:31:32.690 --> 00:31:37.700
The other part is, is this book
suitable for a 12-year-old?

00:31:37.700 --> 00:31:40.317
Like if give this to my daughter
to read, is it suitable?

00:31:40.317 --> 00:31:41.900
And the last part
associated with that

00:31:41.900 --> 00:31:45.460
is, what do I say if I
give her this book to read?

00:31:45.460 --> 00:31:47.200
You know, I attended
this talk at Google.

00:31:47.200 --> 00:31:48.790
I thought it was fascinating.

00:31:48.790 --> 00:31:49.920
Here's a great book.

00:31:49.920 --> 00:31:52.130
I'm almost saying, I
think you're lonely.

00:31:52.130 --> 00:31:54.290
But she might not feel lonely.

00:31:54.290 --> 00:31:56.120
Sorry.

00:31:56.120 --> 00:31:58.120
DAVE MARKS: So I'm not
sure that one got caught,

00:31:58.120 --> 00:31:59.036
but just to reiterate.

00:31:59.036 --> 00:32:00.685
So as for your teenage
daughter, right,

00:32:00.685 --> 00:32:02.310
would this book be
appropriate for her?

00:32:02.310 --> 00:32:04.886
And if you were to get it for
her, what would be a good way

00:32:04.886 --> 00:32:06.760
to present it to her,
rather than being like,

00:32:06.760 --> 00:32:09.010
I think you'd like this?

00:32:09.010 --> 00:32:12.237
KIRA ASATRYAN: I know,
it's an aggressive title.

00:32:12.237 --> 00:32:13.570
AUDIENCE: Yeah, very aggressive.

00:32:13.570 --> 00:32:13.740
KIRA ASATRYAN: It is.

00:32:13.740 --> 00:32:14.522
I fought for it.

00:32:14.522 --> 00:32:15.230
I like the title.

00:32:15.230 --> 00:32:16.510
But, yeah, it is.

00:32:19.449 --> 00:32:21.240
I'm going to do your
second question first.

00:32:21.240 --> 00:32:23.650
Yes, I think it would
be appropriate for her.

00:32:23.650 --> 00:32:27.570
It's about all relationships
not romantic or dating.

00:32:27.570 --> 00:32:30.240
It applies to family
relationships and friends.

00:32:30.240 --> 00:32:32.110
So, yeah, I think
it's appropriate.

00:32:32.110 --> 00:32:35.260
I would probably present
it as like this is just

00:32:35.260 --> 00:32:42.160
a look about relationships or
how to-- I haven't interacted

00:32:42.160 --> 00:32:43.732
with a lot of 12-year-olds.

00:32:43.732 --> 00:32:47.426
But try to make it more
about just like here's

00:32:47.426 --> 00:32:49.920
a book about like social
skills or something,

00:32:49.920 --> 00:32:52.650
than about loneliness,
because that

00:32:52.650 --> 00:32:54.952
might be insulting eventually.

00:32:54.952 --> 00:32:56.410
AUDIENCE: Exactly,
yeah, insulting.

00:32:56.410 --> 00:32:58.670
KIRA ASATRYAN: Yeah, it can be.

00:32:58.670 --> 00:33:00.047
And I forgot your
first question.

00:33:00.047 --> 00:33:01.005
What was the first one?

00:33:01.005 --> 00:33:04.920
AUDIENCE: Oh, because you
wrote the book about yourself,

00:33:04.920 --> 00:33:07.760
do you cover how your state
of mind was at 13-years-old?

00:33:07.760 --> 00:33:09.340
KIRA ASATRYAN: I didn't.

00:33:09.340 --> 00:33:11.230
I only actually talk
about my own story

00:33:11.230 --> 00:33:14.750
at the very, very end, and
it's about being as an adult.

00:33:14.750 --> 00:33:17.110
But I can talk about it now.

00:33:17.110 --> 00:33:20.450
I thought I was depressed
because lonely wasn't really

00:33:20.450 --> 00:33:22.860
a thing in my mind.

00:33:22.860 --> 00:33:25.342
And I kind of think that there
is quite a number of people

00:33:25.342 --> 00:33:28.468
who think they're
depressed, when really it's

00:33:28.468 --> 00:33:33.214
about this issue more
than anything else.

00:33:33.214 --> 00:33:35.752
But I don't know;
I was a good kid,

00:33:35.752 --> 00:33:36.960
so I just kept going with it.

00:33:36.960 --> 00:33:38.460
And then eventually
I was old enough

00:33:38.460 --> 00:33:42.690
to know that it probably
wasn't really my fault. Like,

00:33:42.690 --> 00:33:44.722
I was being nice to people.

00:33:46.812 --> 00:33:48.770
DAVE MARKS: I'll come at
it, if you don't mind,

00:33:48.770 --> 00:33:50.720
because I was a
super angsty teen.

00:33:50.720 --> 00:33:54.090
And the number one thing I
felt was misunderstood, right?

00:33:54.090 --> 00:33:56.341
And I think it was very much
so because I was changing

00:33:56.341 --> 00:33:57.965
every day, and I had
a really hard time

00:33:57.965 --> 00:33:58.950
getting to know myself.

00:33:58.950 --> 00:34:01.500
And so I constantly
felt misunderstood

00:34:01.500 --> 00:34:02.670
by everyone around me.

00:34:02.670 --> 00:34:04.340
Because even they understood
who I was yesterday,

00:34:04.340 --> 00:34:06.756
that's who I am today anymore,
because I'm changing a lot.

00:34:06.756 --> 00:34:10.092
And I'm becoming a
grown man and all this.

00:34:10.092 --> 00:34:11.050
And that's what it was.

00:34:11.050 --> 00:34:13.582
And then when I finally
got to a more state

00:34:13.582 --> 00:34:15.290
where I'm like, oh,
OK, this is who I am,

00:34:15.290 --> 00:34:17.456
I started being able to
share that with people more.

00:34:17.456 --> 00:34:19.320
Then they could
actually understand me.

00:34:19.320 --> 00:34:21.111
I would say that's the
number one adjective

00:34:21.111 --> 00:34:22.360
I felt in my teenage years.

00:34:22.360 --> 00:34:23.859
AUDIENCE: I loved
how you called out

00:34:23.859 --> 00:34:27.179
that focusing on the number
of friends or social media

00:34:27.179 --> 00:34:30.582
contacts doesn't necessarily
get you where you want it,

00:34:30.582 --> 00:34:33.060
that it's almost a fallacy
to look for closeness just

00:34:33.060 --> 00:34:34.340
by quantity.

00:34:34.340 --> 00:34:37.889
Another thought that I had
was, you mentioned, Dave,

00:34:37.889 --> 00:34:40.126
just now being misunderstood.

00:34:40.126 --> 00:34:42.500
I feel like part of the problem
sometimes with loneliness

00:34:42.500 --> 00:34:44.416
is you just don't feel
like there's people who

00:34:44.416 --> 00:34:47.310
get you or can relate to you.

00:34:47.310 --> 00:34:49.420
Everybody has their
own flavor of that.

00:34:49.420 --> 00:34:53.969
From me, I went to a very
broadly Caucasian Catholic high

00:34:53.969 --> 00:34:55.330
school.

00:34:55.330 --> 00:34:57.830
And I come from this Buddhist
family that's vegetarian

00:34:57.830 --> 00:34:59.320
and doesn't drink.

00:34:59.320 --> 00:35:01.284
And so throughout
college, especially,

00:35:01.284 --> 00:35:02.950
you mentioned feeling
lonely in college,

00:35:02.950 --> 00:35:05.390
everybody's a at the frat
house, and I'm the only one,

00:35:05.390 --> 00:35:07.100
and nobody really gets me.

00:35:07.100 --> 00:35:09.220
Now, I thought
it, and I might be

00:35:09.220 --> 00:35:12.690
wrong in this, is that if
I just find people like me,

00:35:12.690 --> 00:35:14.370
that intimacy will be there.

00:35:14.370 --> 00:35:17.357
But I look around today at my
closest friends, the ones who

00:35:17.357 --> 00:35:19.440
we totally get each other;
they're not necessarily

00:35:19.440 --> 00:35:22.850
of the same background as me,
but we have that closeness.

00:35:22.850 --> 00:35:26.490
So do you have to find people
who are really just like you?

00:35:26.490 --> 00:35:29.490
KIRA ASATRYAN: No, you do not.

00:35:29.490 --> 00:35:32.624
In the studies that have been
done, like official research

00:35:32.624 --> 00:35:36.354
social science studies,
it tends to pan out

00:35:36.354 --> 00:35:38.020
that people who are
more like each other

00:35:38.020 --> 00:35:40.460
do like each other more.

00:35:40.460 --> 00:35:45.340
But also, it's a
self-reported thing.

00:35:45.340 --> 00:35:49.220
So they may sort of
be-- the way that it

00:35:49.220 --> 00:35:51.110
being like each other
helps is that you

00:35:51.110 --> 00:35:53.860
don't have to do quite as much
work in the knowing department.

00:35:53.860 --> 00:35:56.850
Like you can just say, I'm
Buddhist, and I'm vegetarian.

00:35:56.850 --> 00:35:58.690
And somebody who
else is like that

00:35:58.690 --> 00:36:00.970
will make that
connection instantly.

00:36:00.970 --> 00:36:03.450
So there's a little
less heavy lifting.

00:36:03.450 --> 00:36:07.970
But it can be done with anybody
who's willing to open up.

00:36:07.970 --> 00:36:10.120
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:36:10.120 --> 00:36:12.934
DAVE MARKS: I'd like to stay
on friendship for a little bit.

00:36:12.934 --> 00:36:14.850
You just mentioned offhand
that people ask you

00:36:14.850 --> 00:36:17.846
for friendship pick-up lines.

00:36:17.846 --> 00:36:19.720
Do you have one you're
like willing to share?

00:36:19.720 --> 00:36:22.210
And, B, I feel
like I moved here,

00:36:22.210 --> 00:36:23.509
that I didn't know anyone.

00:36:23.509 --> 00:36:25.092
And I went through
this period where I

00:36:25.092 --> 00:36:26.940
felt like I was dating friends.

00:36:26.940 --> 00:36:27.940
Do you know what I mean?

00:36:27.940 --> 00:36:28.380
KIRA ASATRYAN: Totally.

00:36:28.380 --> 00:36:30.505
DAVE MARKS: I'd like you
talk about that experience

00:36:30.505 --> 00:36:32.180
and your thoughts on that.

00:36:32.180 --> 00:36:35.496
KIRA ASATRYAN: I think San
Francisco is like a hub of that

00:36:35.496 --> 00:36:37.120
because so many people
are transplants.

00:36:37.120 --> 00:36:40.320
I actually grew up
here, so I did not

00:36:40.320 --> 00:36:43.430
have that exact experience.

00:36:43.430 --> 00:36:45.790
But, yeah, my advice
on that kind of thing

00:36:45.790 --> 00:36:50.320
is if you can tolerate
it, start out in groups.

00:36:50.320 --> 00:36:52.430
Meaning like go to
something that's

00:36:52.430 --> 00:36:55.660
like an interest-based group
or something like that.

00:36:55.660 --> 00:36:59.730
But go there seeking somebody
who you would want to hang out

00:36:59.730 --> 00:37:01.970
with outside of the interest.

00:37:01.970 --> 00:37:06.180
So meaning like, let's say
you like rock climbing.

00:37:06.180 --> 00:37:09.150
A way to meet people is
to go to a rock climbing

00:37:09.150 --> 00:37:10.510
club or something.

00:37:10.510 --> 00:37:12.200
But then try to
identify somebody

00:37:12.200 --> 00:37:15.480
who you want to hang out
with not rock climbing.

00:37:15.480 --> 00:37:17.820
And then those will end
up being your people.

00:37:17.820 --> 00:37:20.460
DAVE MARKS: That's really
good, tangible advice.

00:37:20.460 --> 00:37:23.180
I think the book is full
of good, tangible things

00:37:23.180 --> 00:37:24.267
like that.

00:37:24.267 --> 00:37:25.350
KIRA ASATRYAN: I'm trying.

00:37:25.350 --> 00:37:26.710
DAVE MARKS: Yeah.

00:37:26.710 --> 00:37:27.460
It's hard today.

00:37:27.460 --> 00:37:28.418
How do I make a friend?

00:37:30.082 --> 00:37:32.540
KIRA ASATRYAN: The hardest ones
are the love ones, the love

00:37:32.540 --> 00:37:35.378
question, because who knows?

00:37:35.378 --> 00:37:36.503
How do people fall in love?

00:37:36.503 --> 00:37:37.290
I don't know.

00:37:37.290 --> 00:37:40.060
DAVE MARKS: Been working on it.

00:37:40.060 --> 00:37:42.020
So I guess back to
love relationships,

00:37:42.020 --> 00:37:43.900
you wrote an article
online last week

00:37:43.900 --> 00:37:49.220
that said that single men are
way lonelier than single women,

00:37:49.220 --> 00:37:49.820
which I agree.

00:37:49.820 --> 00:37:54.410
But it's just that single
women are like a little more

00:37:54.410 --> 00:37:55.337
ready to admit it.

00:37:55.337 --> 00:37:56.920
So I feel like a lot
of men-- and I've

00:37:56.920 --> 00:37:59.070
seen this with most my
friends and peers-- feel

00:37:59.070 --> 00:38:02.129
they need to take on like the
lone-wolf mentality, like I

00:38:02.129 --> 00:38:04.170
like being alone, even
though they don't like it.

00:38:04.170 --> 00:38:04.730
I don't want to do it.

00:38:04.730 --> 00:38:06.670
Why do you think men
feel the need to do that?

00:38:06.670 --> 00:38:09.670
And how can I, as like
a somewhat emotionally

00:38:09.670 --> 00:38:11.310
available man,
help my friend feel

00:38:11.310 --> 00:38:12.800
like it's OK to be lonely then?

00:38:12.800 --> 00:38:15.190
KIRA ASATRYAN: Yeah,
that's a great question.

00:38:15.190 --> 00:38:17.314
I think a lot of
it is conditioning.

00:38:17.314 --> 00:38:19.480
I think that some of it is
the way that were raised.

00:38:19.480 --> 00:38:22.480
But this is a fascinating
question for me

00:38:22.480 --> 00:38:25.666
because I thought that the
whole knowing plus caring

00:38:25.666 --> 00:38:29.200
equal closeness thing I thought
it was very gender-neutral.

00:38:29.200 --> 00:38:31.910
But the more I talked to
men, they've been like,

00:38:31.910 --> 00:38:34.610
this isn't really like how
men get close to people,

00:38:34.610 --> 00:38:37.680
or it's not really
realistic or something.

00:38:37.680 --> 00:38:39.060
And I didn't get it.

00:38:39.060 --> 00:38:42.210
But I've been
starting to get it.

00:38:42.210 --> 00:38:44.600
And I think that
this not wanting

00:38:44.600 --> 00:38:48.700
to show any problems
in your social life

00:38:48.700 --> 00:38:51.390
is a big, big part of
it and just the way

00:38:51.390 --> 00:38:53.847
that men are taught to be.

00:38:53.847 --> 00:38:55.930
DAVE MARKS: Do you think
it's legitimate that they

00:38:55.930 --> 00:38:57.096
say this won't work for men?

00:38:57.096 --> 00:39:03.470
Or men have been conditioned
to make it not work for them?

00:39:03.470 --> 00:39:05.117
For me, I related
to it very much.

00:39:05.117 --> 00:39:06.450
I thought it was a good formula.

00:39:06.450 --> 00:39:07.430
Like you know someone.

00:39:07.430 --> 00:39:08.290
You care about them.

00:39:08.290 --> 00:39:09.360
You'll become close to them.

00:39:09.360 --> 00:39:10.840
I thought it made
perfect sense and aligned

00:39:10.840 --> 00:39:13.006
with a lot of experiences
I've seen in my real life.

00:39:13.006 --> 00:39:15.250
KIRA ASATRYAN: I
think that for guys--

00:39:15.250 --> 00:39:18.200
so the book basically takes
the romantic component out

00:39:18.200 --> 00:39:21.970
of it, because then it was
going to be about intimacy,

00:39:21.970 --> 00:39:23.557
and then it couldn't
apply really

00:39:23.557 --> 00:39:25.640
to friendships and family
in the same kind of way.

00:39:25.640 --> 00:39:27.120
And I don't want to go there.

00:39:27.120 --> 00:39:29.220
But I think that the
intimacy, meaning

00:39:29.220 --> 00:39:32.590
like romantic types
of relationships,

00:39:32.590 --> 00:39:36.340
I think that men are more--
they need that a little bit more

00:39:36.340 --> 00:39:37.540
than women do.

00:39:37.540 --> 00:39:42.020
Like totally not romantic female
friendships are very common,

00:39:42.020 --> 00:39:46.330
and they're quite a bit more
easy for women to develop.

00:39:46.330 --> 00:39:48.980
And I think it's how we're
socialized, personally.

00:39:48.980 --> 00:39:53.310
Eons of women have been
sitting around weaving,

00:39:53.310 --> 00:39:55.920
talking to each other
and becoming friends.

00:39:55.920 --> 00:39:58.076
But for men, it's been
a little bit different.

00:39:58.076 --> 00:39:59.200
And our brains are ancient.

00:40:01.614 --> 00:40:03.530
DAVE MARKS: There's a
lot of studies out there

00:40:03.530 --> 00:40:05.980
that say a majority of men lose
a lot of their close friends

00:40:05.980 --> 00:40:07.980
in their 20s because they
don't know how to keep them.

00:40:07.980 --> 00:40:09.438
KIRA ASATRYAN: They
do, and there's

00:40:09.438 --> 00:40:11.290
this idea of
closeness in the doing

00:40:11.290 --> 00:40:14.544
is what it's called in the
social sciences, where men

00:40:14.544 --> 00:40:16.210
think that they stay
close to each other

00:40:16.210 --> 00:40:18.240
by doing things together.

00:40:18.240 --> 00:40:19.881
And they kind of don't.

00:40:19.881 --> 00:40:21.380
Like they think
if they go golfing

00:40:21.380 --> 00:40:24.180
with their friend for
20 years that they know

00:40:24.180 --> 00:40:25.470
stuff about them.

00:40:25.470 --> 00:40:27.710
And then at the end of those
20 years, they're like,

00:40:27.710 --> 00:40:29.400
I don't really know
that guy at all.

00:40:29.400 --> 00:40:30.191
We're just friends.

00:40:33.729 --> 00:40:36.020
DAVE MARKS: So I think we
have time for about one more.

00:40:36.020 --> 00:40:38.269
I'd like to offer it to
someone in the audience, who'd

00:40:38.269 --> 00:40:40.360
like to finish those off.

00:40:40.360 --> 00:40:43.380
But if not, I have one
we can close out on.

00:40:43.380 --> 00:40:46.140
All right, so it's Friday.

00:40:46.140 --> 00:40:47.807
It's national Unplugging Day.

00:40:47.807 --> 00:40:49.390
KIRA ASATRYAN: Oh,
yeah, that's right.

00:40:49.390 --> 00:40:50.740
DAVE MARKS: And so I
assume a lot of people

00:40:50.740 --> 00:40:53.170
will be going out and doing
social things tonight.

00:40:53.170 --> 00:40:55.753
You said something in the book
that I identify with very much.

00:40:55.753 --> 00:40:58.830
You say, "I found mediocre
social interactions only made

00:40:58.830 --> 00:41:00.000
me more lonely," right?

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:01.450
And I agree with that very much.

00:41:01.450 --> 00:41:03.220
You think like going out
and being with friends will

00:41:03.220 --> 00:41:04.011
make you feel good.

00:41:04.011 --> 00:41:06.240
And then you go home, and
you just feel more alone

00:41:06.240 --> 00:41:09.030
than before it started.

00:41:09.030 --> 00:41:10.720
Do you have any
recommendations of how

00:41:10.720 --> 00:41:13.720
we can take mediocre
social interactions

00:41:13.720 --> 00:41:15.704
to closer social interactions?

00:41:15.704 --> 00:41:17.120
You know, if you're
at this party,

00:41:17.120 --> 00:41:18.580
maybe there's
nonsense small talk,

00:41:18.580 --> 00:41:20.996
or you feel like you don't
connect with any of the people,

00:41:20.996 --> 00:41:24.160
how can we change that?

00:41:24.160 --> 00:41:27.690
KIRA ASATRYAN: I'm going to
say something a little fruity

00:41:27.690 --> 00:41:29.146
because I feel like it.

00:41:29.146 --> 00:41:30.770
I think the one thing
you can really do

00:41:30.770 --> 00:41:34.490
is be a little braver,
be a little bit bolder.

00:41:34.490 --> 00:41:35.900
Because the people
that tend to--

00:41:35.900 --> 00:41:37.230
and this is a generalization.

00:41:37.230 --> 00:41:39.790
But the people that
tend to feel that way,

00:41:39.790 --> 00:41:42.990
are the more timid people in
social interactions, especially

00:41:42.990 --> 00:41:45.120
groups.

00:41:45.120 --> 00:41:48.620
So ask a question that you
think might be a little too

00:41:48.620 --> 00:41:52.500
personal, because
probably they won't mind.

00:41:52.500 --> 00:41:55.000
It's much more likely that they
won't mind than that they'll

00:41:55.000 --> 00:41:57.740
be offended or something.

00:41:57.740 --> 00:41:58.560
That's my advice.

00:41:58.560 --> 00:42:00.595
DAVE MARKS: I like it a lot.

00:42:00.595 --> 00:42:03.280
So the book's "Stop Being
Lonely," Kira Asatryan,

00:42:03.280 --> 00:42:04.540
available at the back for $10.

00:42:04.540 --> 00:42:05.998
Kira, thank you so
much for coming.

00:42:05.998 --> 00:42:07.300
We really appreciate it.

